<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: BOGOTA; SHADOW OF SCANDAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ernesto Samper will be sworn in as president of Colombia Sunday amid a 
simmering scandal over attempts by cocaine traffickers to finance Samper's 
electoral campaign. 
</P>
<P>
 Samper has conceded that leaders of the Cali cartel, who control 80% of the 
international cocaine trade, offered money, but he denies accepting it. The 
allegations, which came to light with the release of secret recordings of the 
traffickers discussing their plans, alarmed U.S. officials and raised concerns 
about Colombia's resolve to continue the war on drugs. 
</P>
<P>
 An economist and longtime Liberal Party political insider, Samper won a narrow 
election victory June 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
