<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOTHER KILLS 3 CHILDREN, HERSELF AT RESORT CONDO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHAWN HUBLER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 31-year-old woman, apparently despondent over having to return her children 
to the custody of their father in Long Beach, killed herself and her three 
small daughters this weekend in a $350-a-night resort condominium in posh 
Indian Wells, authorities said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 The bodies of Terri Lynn Esterak, a Rancho Mirage resident, and her children 
-- 9-year-old Erica, 3-year-old Eden and 16-month-old Erin -- were found about 
12:30 p.m. Monday at the Hyatt Grand Champion Villas, said Riverside Deputy 
Coroner Lisa Banasiak. 
</P>
<P>
 The children, Banasiak said, had spent July with their mother, and were 
scheduled to be returned this month to the custody of their father, Michael 
Esterak of Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 The deputy added that the mother had left a suicide note, but he would not 
divulge the contents. The father could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
 Riverside County Sheriff's Sgt. John Sebastian said the room at the Hyatt had 
been double-locked when hotel housekeepers arrived to clean it Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
 Security guards opened the door to find the pajama-clad bodies of the three 
little girls piled on the bed with their mother. 
</P>
<P>
 The sergeant said it was unclear what time the shootings occurred because no 
gunshots were reported by hotel guests. 
</P>
<P>
 The woman, he said, had checked into one of the hotel's most exclusive 
condominiums on Saturday; hotel employees told police they had not noticed any 
strange behavior on her part. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's just terrible," Sebastian said. "We have acts of violence in our area, 
but this hits harder because of the nature of the crime and the kids involved. 
</P>
<P>
 "We deal with these things in our careers, but . . . it's really hard," he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Indian Wells is about 110 miles east of Los Angeles. 
</P>
